RATIONALE: IEC 61508-3:2010, Clause 7.9.2.2(b).

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: SVP-021
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Static versus dynamic validation techniques
STATEMENT: >>>
The following mix of static and dynamic techniques is selected for software
validation:

Static techniques (no execution of the software under test):
- Formal review and inspection of safety function logic against the SSRS.
- Static analysis of the software in the target configuration using
  <static analysis tool, version>.
- Formal proof or abstract interpretation for <specific modules>, if
  required at the target SIL.

Dynamic techniques (execution-based):
- Functional testing on target hardware covering all EUC operating modes.
- Fault injection testing to verify diagnostic coverage.
- Performance and timing testing under representative load profiles.

Rationale: <Describe why this combination is appropriate for the target SIL
and the nature of the safety functions. Note: IEC 61508-3:2010 Table A.6
lists static analysis as HR at SIL 2-4; dynamic testing on target hardware
is HR at all SIL levels.>
<<<
SIL_1: HR
SIL_2: HR
SIL_3: HR
SIL_4: HR
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection
RATIONALE: IEC 61508-3:2010, Clause 7.9.2.2(b) and Table A.6.

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: SVP-022
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Analytical versus statistical validation methods
STATEMENT: >>>
The basis for generating validation test cases shall be:

Analytical (deterministic) methods — primary approach:
- Requirements-based testing: each safety function requirement in the SSRS
  shall have at least one validation test case demonstrating correct behaviour.
- Boundary-value analysis for all numeric inputs and outputs.
- Equivalence partitioning for input domains with defined valid/invalid ranges.
- Cause-effect analysis for safety function logic with multiple input
  conditions.

Statistical methods (where applicable):
- <Describe if statistical testing (e.g. operational profile testing per
  IEC 61508-7:2010 Annex B) is planned. State the operational profile source
  and the confidence level target.>
- <If not applicable, state: "Statistical testing methods are not used in
  this validation; all test cases are derived analytically from the SSRS.">

Rationale: <Explain why the chosen methods are appropriate for the safety
functions and the target SIL.>
<<<
SIL_1: HR
SIL_2: HR
SIL_3: HR
SIL_4: HR
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection
RATIONALE: IEC 61508-3:2010, Clause 7.9.2.2(b).

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: SVP-023
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Acceptance criteria basis
STATEMENT: >>>
Validation acceptance criteria shall be based primarily on objective,
measurable factors:
- Exact match of output values to expected values within defined tolerances.
- Timing and response-time constraints derived from the SSRS.
- Memory and resource usage within specified limits.
- Zero unresolved safety-critical failures at the completion of validation.

Expert judgement may be used as an acceptance basis only when objective
criteria cannot be defined, and shall be:
a) Exercised by a person with demonstrated competence in the relevant domain.
b) Documented in sufficient detail to allow independent review.
c) Approved by the Software Safety Manager before the result is accepted.

For SIL 3 and SIL 4 projects, the threshold for using expert judgement and
the identity of the expert shall be agreed with the FSA in advance
(see SVP-081).
<<<
SIL_1: R
SIL_2: R
SIL_3: HR
SIL_4: HR
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection
RATIONALE: IEC 61508-3:2010, Clause 7.9.2.2(d).

